To determine “real-scenario” performance accurately, catalysts must be tested in assembled cells, such as the electrolyzers shown in Fig. 17a, b. Yamanaka et al. conducted pioneering studies by combining electrochemical H2O2 production and H-type proton exchange membrane (PEM) fuel cells (Fig. 17a), in which protons were supplied by the evolution of O2 from water in the anode chamber [16]. This setup eliminated the use of H2, which eliminated the extra transportation costs and safety concerns arising from H2 usage. In 2018, Yamanaka and coworkers reported that the concentration of H2O2 produced in this configuration was as high as 18.7 wt.% when a Co–Nx/C material was used as the cathode catalyst [143]. In addition to H-type fuel cells, conventional flow cells have also been used to produce H2O2 with O2 insufflation, and this was even combined with furfural oxidation to generate 2-furoic acid at the anode [6]. With this protocol, the levels of H2O2 generation at the cathode and 2-furoic acid generation at the anode reached 9.66 mol h−1gcat-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
